[{"id":"VR797913","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a semicircular arc with center C and radius R.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR797913.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A semicircular arc of charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"positive uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> has a radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> and subtends an angle of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"180\"><math alttext=\"180\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>180</mn></math></span></span> degrees about Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span>, as shown in the figure. The charge is distributed uniformly around the arc. Which of the following claims about the electric field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span> is correct, and what evidence or reasoning helps support the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR797913_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field is zero at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span>. Because of symmetry, at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span> there is no preferred direction for a nonzero field to point.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field is zero at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span>. Contributions to the electric field from the top half of the arc cancel the field contributions from the bottom half of the arc.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field has a nonzero magnitude at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span>. The field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span> is the same as the field of a positive point charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"positive uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> located a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R over 2\"><math alttext=\"R over 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></span></span> to the left of Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field has a nonzero magnitude at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span>. Every point on the arc produces a field at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></span></span> that cancels the vertical, but not the horizontal, field component from another point on the arc.</p>"],"answer":3}]